[2] Pakistan (Sindh)
Date: Thu 1 Apr 2021
Source: ARY News [abridged, edited]
https://arynews.tv/en/measles-breaks-out-jacobabad-shikarpur-districts-sindh/


An outbreak of measles cases has been reported in the northern Sindh districts of Jacobabad and Shikarpur, quoting health officials, ARY News reported on Thursday [1 Apr 2021].

Sindh health department has sent its team to the area after several cases of measles were reported in children in Jacobabad, Thul, Garhi Yaseen and other towns. The team also comprises officials of the World Health Organization (WHO), UNICEF and the Expanded Programme on Immunisation (EPI).

"In March [2021], 75 children infected with measles were brought to the National Institute of Child Health (NICH) in Karachi," NICH head Dr. Jamal Raza said. "In last 3 months over 160 children were brought to the hospital," the NICH chief said. "Fifty percent children of them from other districts were infected with measles," Dr. Raza said.

"Measles is a dangerous and deadly disease for children. Most of the parents avoided measles vaccination to children owing to coronavirus and large number of children remained [who had not had a measles] inoculation," Prof. Jamal Raza said.

"Vaccination is the only safety for children against measles," he said. "Measles is a major cause of the children's death," Dr. Raza said.

According to experts, the respiratory disease is considered to be a highly virulent infection. Nearly 1 to 3 of every 1000 children infected with measles are likely to die from respiratory and neurological complications. Common complications include diarrhea, middle ear infection and pneumonia, which is the major cause of deaths of children with measles.

